<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-45-0713 </DOCNO><TEXT>This book demonstrates the use of the personal computer as an integralcomponent of legal decision-making. It gives the reader the techniquesnecessary to examine and evaluate the variables that contribute to adecision and to make a judgment with statistical confidence. Nagel beginswith an overview of the use of the microcomputer as a tool in the legaldecision-making process. He reviews in detail the currently availabledecision-aiding software. Several important areas of decision-makingare covered, including predicting the outcome of future cases in lightof previous relevant cases and present facts, litigation choices includingwhether to go to trial or to settle, allocating attorney resources, andnegotiating and mediating.</TEXT></DOC>